[3]
Date: Mon 3 Oct 2011
Source: Bloomberg Businessweek [edited]
http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9Q4VLJG1.htm


An elderly woman from East Baton Rouge Parish died over the weekend
[1-2 Oct 2011] after being diagnosed with listeriosis, Louisiana's
state epidemiologist, Dr Raoult Ratard, said Monday [3 Oct 2011]. The
woman had eaten cantaloupe 2 or 3 weeks earlier, but her family didn't
know which store or state it came from, he said.

Investigators will try to learn whether the _Listeria_ is the same
strain found in Colorado cantaloupe recalled because of the bacterium,
but it will take at least a week to grow and test the bacteria and the
tests may be inconclusive, Ratard said.

Cantaloupe from Jensen Farms in Colorado has been linked to 84
illnesses and as many as 17 deaths in 19 states.

State officials said Friday [30 Sep 2011] that Jensen Farms had added
Louisiana to its recall list for cantaloupes shipped between 29 Jul
and 10 Sep 2011.

The fatal infection is the only listeriosis case reported since July
2011 in Louisiana, Ratard said. "By now any (recalled) cantaloupe left
would be rotten. So it looks like the danger from cantaloupe is very
low now," Ratard said. "But you never know. Something else may come
up."

_Listeria_ is common in soil and water, according to the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention. The CDC's website says it can be found
in uncooked meats and vegetables, unpasteurized milk and cheese made
from unpasteurized milk, and processed meats, smoked seafood, and soft
cheeses that become contaminated after cooking and processing. And
since it can take a month or more for symptoms to show up, people who
ate contaminated cantaloupe before the recall could still get sick.

Symptoms can vary widely. The CDC says older adults and people with
immune system disorders are most likely to develop blood poisoning and
meningitis, which can cause headache, stiff neck, confusion, loss of
balance, and convulsions. Pregnant women may have a mild, flu-like
illness followed by a miscarriage or a life-threatening illness in the
newborn. People whose immune systems are in good shape may not feel
sick or might get high fever and muscle aches, with diarrhea, nausea,
or vomiting sometimes coming first.

[Byline: Janet McConnaughey]

