<promed@promedmail.org>

[As of 3 Oct 2011, a total of 100 persons infected with any of the 4
outbreak-associated strains of _Listeria monocytogenes_ have been
reported to CDC from 20 states. 18 deaths were reported from 8 states.
Listeriosis is known to be more severe in the elderly and almost 90
percent were 60 years of age or greater in the current outbreak. 2
were pregnant. Although, most pregnant women may experience mild
illness, maternal bacteremia can result in intrauterine infection that
may be followed by fetal loss or neonatal infection. No mention is
made of associated miscarriages, stillbirths, or neonatal infection in
this current outbreak. More cases likely will be reported because of
the long incubation period (up to one month or more) and the time
needed for diagnosis of this disease.

For comparison, in a prior large, national listeriosis outbreak that
was associated with contaminated frankfurters, 108 cases were reported
with 14 associated deaths and 4 miscarriages or stillbirths (Mead, PS,
Dunne EF, Graves L, et al: Nationwide outbreak of listeriosis due to
contaminated meat. Epidemiol Infect 2006; 134(4): 744-51; available at
http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2870438) and in a prior
large outbreak that was associated with Mexican-style cheese, 142
cases were reported with 48 deaths: 20 fetuses, 10 neonates, and 18
non pregnant adults (Linnan, MJ, Mascola L, Lou XD, et al: Epidemic
listeriosis associated with Mexican-style cheese. N Engl J Med 1988;
319(13): 823-8; abstract available at
http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJM198809293191303). - Mod.ML]
